metadata.name: Scaffold #197
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: vapour trails #73
metadata.description:
“first you look so strong, then you fade away
the sun will blind my eyes, i’ll love you anyway
thirsty for your smile, i watch you for a while
you are a vapour trail in a deep blue sky”

— Andy Bell (Ride) (1991)

this collection tries to capture that feeling of lying in the grass
in a park
staring at the sky
fantasizing about your love (if they even exist)
playing out different paths
while smoke from your cigarette (jazz or otherwise)
trails between you and the faraway of everything
feeling grateful to not have to be anywhere
but here (now)

with luck
they lay next to you
and silently you appreciate each tick of the clock
wasted together
until life again gets in the way
and pulls you back
into the fray

metadata.name: FairyCells II #300
metadata.description:
FairyCells II is intended as a logical continuation of the first FairyCells series. By dropping the plotter drawing constraint, new perspectives for exploration appeared.
This is how these cells began to intertwine, live together, mutate and change color, like an evolving system.

What surprises me the most in this new series, is the stories appearing behind each new composition. See how these abstracts shapes can come to life and narrate us things through our imagination.

Each color palette takes us into a different world, drawing a very specific atmosphere.

As me, let yourself be carried away by these stories 💫 !

Artwork by Julien_Espagnon, 2022.

Control : Press « S » to save the image as a PNG.

metadata.name: Enfantines II. Enfantillages Pittoresques #433
metadata.description:
The Enfantines are three sets of beginner piano pieces by Erik Satie, written with the aim of preparing children for the sound patterns of modern music. Composed in 1913, these are genuine children’s pieces, crafted for small hands, easy to learn. 

“Enfantines II. Enfantillages Pittoresques” is the second of a set of algorithms that explore the basics of Generative Art, written with the aim of preparing artists for the script patterns of digital life. “Enfantillages Pittoresques” experiments with predefined plots, colour blending, webgl shaders, and generative music; all with a fresh, childish style. This algorithm has been trained to draw basic shapes in accordance to Satie’s lyrics. However, it uses them in unusual ways and creates what looks like fantastic creatures, microscopic beings, or, to follow Corneille, Constant, and Appel: "human animals".

“It took me four years to paint like Raphael, but a lifetime to paint like a child” Attributed to Picasso (falsely, probably)

With two modes that won’t produce the same outputs, “Enfantines” are best experienced twice. In music mode, the code uses Satie’s piano composition as a way of taming randomness, the sounds affecting the parameters of the strokes.

Hey, these have won me congratulations from the Shah of Persia and the King of Yvetot!


# INTERACTIVITY
Press M or Double Tap (mobile) for AUDIO mode
Wait for SILENT mode
Press I for Trait Info (desktop)
Press 1 for Canvas Save (desktop)

Introduce “?pixelDensity=171” after URL for FULL SCREEN MODE (pseudo-deterministic).
Introduce “?pixelDensity=X” for HQ renders (standard is 2, and 8 produces 400ppi 40x44cm prints).


# EASY-TO-READ CODE
The “Enfantines” are educational algorithms. The code has been compressed and minified for a performance boost, but can be read fully in GitHub: https://github.com/ratchitect/


# PERFORMANCE
Better experienced with Chrome.

metadata.name: Tendencies #7
metadata.description:
Tendencies is the first in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

Zajec's generative work was motivated by redundancy in his paintings: "The monotony of the manual task and the limited number of variations which I was able to produce in a given time made me realize the inadequacy of traditional methods in dealing with our present reality." Tendencies was inspired by — and pays tribute to — one if Zajec's earliest forays into generative creation: a work titled RAM 10 V.15, which was written on an IBM 1620 and programmed in FORTRAN.

The title of the collection itself is a reference to the first exhibition of Zajec's RAM series, while the number of editions minted referencing the year Zajec put plotter to paper.

Made in p5js
Created December 2022
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: Digital Surrogates #86
metadata.description:
“Allan McCollum’s Plaster Surrogates was a thought-provoking series of sculptures that examines the role of art in contemporary society. The sculptures are cast from plaster and painted to resemble frames, mats, and black rectangles, creating a visual illusion of empty picture frames. McCollum's intention with the surrogates was to comment on the mass production and consumption of art objects, as well as the way in which art is often valued for its social function rather than its inherent aesthetic qualities.”

Continuing the integration of generative art and conceptual art, this work is a digital reproduction and inspiration of Plaster Surrogates - 1982 by noted conceptual artist, Allan McCollum.

Even though the original work had completely black rectangles, in this work, contrasting colors are used in some variations to increase the beauty. The dimensions and colors of the frames are calculated according to McCollum's original work. Various color palettes and canvas sizes have been used.

-----------

No images are used, created entirely by coding. Textures such as wood, canvas, and oil paint have been created to create a realistic look. Preview optimized for fxhash capturing system and full rendering can take up to several minutes, so I highly recommend checking out this artwork in high quality.


To save the artwork in high resolution, Open it in the live mode, it will be saved automatically after completion.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Tema #51
metadata.description:
Tema is the second in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

After gaining some traction with his original collection RAM, Zajec and his collaborating programmer Matjaz Hmeljak undertook a more complex algorithm titled "The Cube: Theme and Variation" (or TVC). The program laid out 8 unique elements in a grid, creating a three-dimensional viewing of objects in space. They published a paper about the underlying algorithm, found at: http://www.edwardzajec.com/tvc4/pil1/index.html

TVC was first printed in 1971, shortly after Zajec returned to Italy following his artistic studies in the US. It was programmed on an IBM 9044 & printed with a CalComp 563 plotter.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: Adjacent #168
metadata.description:
Adjacent is the third in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art. This piece focuses on the study of Diagonal White, a series he developed between 1970 and 1975.

In 1976, Ruth Leavitt published a collection of papers titled "Artist & Computer", which highlighted the 35 prominent generative artists and asked them to discuss their work. They were posed questions like, "Do you feel art work created with a computer has now or will have an impact on art as a whole in the future?". Edward Zajec was a subject of one of those papers and in it detailed the approach to Diagonal White. 

The original program was run on a CDC 6200 computer at The Univeresiry of Trieste. The programming was done in collaboration with Dr. Matjaz Hmeljak, his long-time technical partner. Inspired by his collaborative relationship, Adjacent the output of a partnership between Christine Hall and Chris Maddern.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall and @chrismaddern

metadata.name: Valley of Empty Future #6
metadata.description:
*translated from drone swarm operator 51b13*
Preliminary analysis of the planet's atmosphere suggest an increased concentration of carbon monoxide, consistent with temperature readings.
No fauna or flora detected on immediate surface. Even though soil spectroscopy confirm presence of organic compounds, samples must be collected in order to have definitive results.

Scouts have confirmed, trough x-ray and radar imaging, sprawling areas of artificial environments. High density of buildings suggest an intricate and highly developed societal structure, with only it's tallest buildings piercing trough the meters deep silicate dust covering most of the area. It intrigues me why build so high, would these be religious monuments to be seen by all, for their exuberance? Immediately forwarding digital reconstruction of the -cities?- for Cosmic Sociologists to further speculate on their purposes.

////

On fullscreen view, press P to download a 1920*2560 PNG

Made in Cables.gl
